On HIV, noncommunicable diseases in eight key points
GENEVA - Noncommunicable diseases (NCDs), such as cardiovascular diseases, strokes, cancer, diabetes, and chronic respiratory diseases, are responsible for 70% of all deaths.
There is irrefutable evidence that tobacco use, sedentary behavior, poor diet, and excessive alcohol consumption increase the risk of dying prematurely from noncommunicable diseases.
Despite widespread knowledge of the risks, obesity on a global scale is generally not controlled, while tobacco and alcohol consumption continue to rise.
It was in this context that networks of alliances for noncommunicable diseases convened from December 9 to 11 for the second Global Forum of the Alliance for Noncommunicable Diseases in the United Arab Emirates.
In their search for solutions aimed at regulating NCDs, they should draw inspiration from the HIV fight movement.
People living with and affected by HIV continue to lead interventions, and their unique form of mobilization has been essential to the progress achieved.
While the battle is not over, AIDS activists know they can win this battle.
Similarly, a mobilization movement against NMTs can curb this epidemic.
However, in 2015, Richard Horton, the editor-in-chief of The Lancet, described the NMT community as being in need of an "electroshock to its semi-comatose mind." He added: "But who will have the courage to deliver it?"
We believe there are lessons to be learned from the AIDS activism movement.
While global attention focuses on preventing NCDs, those striving to control avoidable diseases should draw inspiration from the ABCs of AIDS-fighting organizations.
The first letter that the NMT community must take into account is "A", for activism.
Any person over 40 years old surely remembers the images of AIDS activism advocates participating in "die-in" protests at scientific conferences around the world.
In the United States, AIDS activism advocates took to the streets and even shut down the Food and Drug Administration headquarters for a day in October 1988.
At a global level, activists have pressured governments and pharmaceutical companies to make medications more affordable.
This activism continues and should serve as a model for action on noncommunicable diseases.
Then, the NMT Community must adopt a bolder approach to budgets - the "B" of the AIDS-fighting movement's strategy.
Civic organizations and grassroots activism can mobilize initial energy, but organizing and maintaining a broad coalition requires funding.
The AIDS-fighting movement was clear about this from the beginning and pressed for resources to effectively support its awareness and accountability activities.
"C" represents coalitions: the AIDS-fighting movements did not take long to realize that progress comes only with multiple supporters.
Activists have established connections between people living with HIV and those concerned with other issues, such as women's rights, intellectual property, nutrition, and housing.
Coalitions and specialized campaigns function better when they bring together internal and external leaders in government, combining their perspectives and expertise.
The AIDS-fighting movement also understood that a comprehensive response to the epidemic is essential to spreading its support.
Thus, "D", the key determinant of success, consisted of 'drawing attention to the interconnectedness of the challenge.'
For example, lobbying education leaders to keep girls in school longer has contributed to providing young people with the knowledge and power to make informed decisions about when and with whom to negotiate protected sexual relationships.
Links have also been established between groups working on poverty, gender equality, and nutrition: all factors that played a key role in the AIDS crisis.
Non-communicable diseases are not less isolated in their causality and also benefit from a multisectoral approach to prevention.
"E" represents engagement - this is what helped the AIDS-fighting movement gain such great influence.
By drawing on strategic borrowings from the disability rights movement, which championed the key phrase "Nothing about us without us," AIDS advocates demanded the involvement of existing organizations in treating the disease.
For example, UNAIDS remains the only United Nations agency with seats on its Governing Board for representatives of civil society.
This norm is so deeply integrated into the AIDS-fighting movement that it would be almost unthinkable for an AIDS meeting to take place without representation from the community.
Disease prevention movements must also develop compelling narratives, and "F" - framing the question - is essential for the AIDS community to secure political leadership support.
In particular, access to AIDS treatments has been presented as an issue of economic justice.
Formulating the narrative this way leads to a significant reduction in drug prices, to the point where more than half of the people living with HIV in low- and middle-income countries are on treatment.
An equally important formulation of the question for AIDS, and very pertinent for the NMT movement, is that of accountability.
The AIDS community has worked hard to place more emphasis on individual choices, rather than attributing responsibility to the state for providing health care and eliminating legal discrimination.
In the AIDS debate, gender - the "G" of our movement - has been a significant point.
HIV was initially regarded as a "disease of gay men," and gender identity became rooted from the outset in the DNA of the AIDS-fighting movement.
The gender dimensions of these diseases are no less important: one needs only to examine the way alcohol and tobacco are marketed to understand this.
Gender, therefore, must become a focal point of the NMT prevention efforts.
Finally, "H" - human rights - is the foundation of the AIDS response.
Campaigns have been launched against workplace discrimination, in schools, and in medical centers.
The strategic litigation has ensured equality under the law.
The AIDS fighting movement refused to hold major conferences in countries with repressive laws against people living with HIV.
The NMT movement could adopt the same tactic, for example, by refusing to meet in countries that fail to limit unhealthy food advertising to children.
We could continue through the alphabet listing the lessons learned from the AIDS fight, but we believe it appropriate to conclude with "H," given that human rights provided the response to AIDS and should provide the response to non-communicable diseases.
Poverty, exclusion, as well as social and economic marginalization, increase people's vulnerability to HIV.
It is the same for NMT.
The first reaction to the AIDS epidemic was to wonder: "Why don't these people make better choices?" The AIDS activism movement clearly stated that this question is not the right one.
Today, with 70% of the planet at risk of premature death from avoidable diseases, "these people" represent a large number of us.
The NMT and AIDS communities can learn from each other.
We are a stronger movement when we unite our forces.
The opinions expressed here do not necessarily reflect those of UNAIDS.
